1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,280
- The Pandorica is opening.
- What is it?

2
00:00:04,400 --> 00:00:08,160
Box, cage, prison? It was built to contain
the most feared thing in all the universe.

3
00:00:08,240 --> 00:00:10,800
Anything that powerful,
I'd know about it.

4
00:00:10,880 --> 00:00:13,200
Everything that ever hated you
is coming here tonight.

5
00:00:13,320 --> 00:00:17,080
They're all here, all of them.
All for you. What could you possibly be?

6
00:00:17,160 --> 00:00:20,640
If something can be remembered,
it can come back.

7
00:00:20,720 --> 00:00:22,040
Hello, Amy.

8
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:25,000
- But you died. How can you be here?
- What's your name?

9
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:28,040
- Rory. How can she not remember me?
- Because you never existed.

10
00:00:28,120 --> 00:00:31,360
Who are those Romans?
They're not real. They can't be.

11
00:00:31,440 --> 00:00:33,800
They're all in a book
in Amy's house.

12
00:00:33,880 --> 00:00:37,720
- It's a trap. It has to be.
- Plastic Romans. Duplicates!

13
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:42,600
Listen to me, you have to run.
I'm a thing. I'll kill you. Just go!

14
00:00:42,720 --> 00:00:46,000
There's something wrong with the TARDIS.
Something else is controlling it.

15
00:00:46,080 --> 00:00:47,720
26th June 2010.

16
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:53,160
DALEK: A scenario was devised
from the memories of your companion.

17
00:00:53,240 --> 00:00:55,320
Rory Williams from Leadworth.

18
00:00:55,400 --> 00:00:57,640
My boyfriend.
How could I ever forget you?

19
00:00:57,720 --> 00:01:01,240
DALEK: The cracks in time
are the work of the Doctor.

20
00:01:01,320 --> 00:01:04,800
- The Pandorica is ready.
- Ready for what?

21
00:01:04,880 --> 00:01:07,760
DALEK: Ready for you.

22
00:01:08,760 --> 00:01:11,560
Every sun will supernova
at every moment in history.

23
00:01:11,640 --> 00:01:16,040
The whole universe will never
have existed! Listen to me!

24
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:37,360
(WIND WHISTLING)

25
00:01:41,280 --> 00:01:43,040
(OWL HOOTS)

26
00:01:52,400 --> 00:01:55,160
(SWING SQUEAKS)

27
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:02,480
Dear Santa. Thank you for the dolls
and pencils and the fish.

28
00:02:02,560 --> 00:02:05,360
It's Easter now,
so I hope I didn't wake you,

29
00:02:05,440 --> 00:02:10,400
but, honest, it is an emergency.

30
00:02:10,480 --> 00:02:13,400
There's a crack in my wall.

31
00:02:15,640 --> 00:02:18,280
Aunt Sharon says
it's just an ordinary crack,

32
00:02:18,360 --> 00:02:21,240
but I know it's not, cos at night,
there's voices.

33
00:02:21,320 --> 00:02:26,240
So, please, please, could you
send someone to fix it?

34
00:02:26,320 --> 00:02:28,160
Or a policeman. Or...

35
00:02:31,440 --> 00:02:33,680
(RUSHING OF WIND)

36
00:02:38,120 --> 00:02:39,600
Back in a moment.

37
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:02,760
It's a lovely painting, Amelia.

38
00:03:04,640 --> 00:03:06,920
And what are all these?

39
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:08,800
Stars.

40
00:03:08,880 --> 00:03:10,400
Oh, Amelia!

41
00:03:11,960 --> 00:03:13,480
Tell you what,

42
00:03:13,560 --> 00:03:15,120
shall we go outside?

43
00:03:18,240 --> 00:03:20,920
What do you see, Amelia?

44
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:22,600
The moon.

45
00:03:22,680 --> 00:03:24,320
And what else?

46
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:27,960
- Just the dark.
- But no stars.

47
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:33,000
If there were stars up there,
we'd be able to see them, wouldn't we?

48
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:35,680
Amelia, look at me.

49
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:42,000
You know this is all just a story,
don't you?

50
00:03:42,080 --> 00:03:44,400
You know there's no such thing as stars.

51
00:03:56,840 --> 00:03:58,800
(MUFFLED CONVERSATION
FROM DOWNSTAIRS)

52
00:03:58,880 --> 00:04:00,280
It's quite common, actually.

53
00:04:00,320 --> 00:04:03,640
Throughout history, people have talked
about seeing stars in the sky.

54
00:04:03,720 --> 00:04:05,240
God knows where it comes from.

55
00:04:05,280 --> 00:04:08,720
AUNT SHARON: I just don't want her growing
up and joining one of those Star Cults.

56
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:11,160
I don't trust that Richard Dawkins.

57
00:04:51,880 --> 00:04:53,560
Come on, Aunt Sharon.

58
00:04:53,640 --> 00:04:57,120
- Look at that! That's good, isn't it?
- Not that! This way.

59
00:04:57,200 --> 00:05:00,040
- But we're not looking at anything.
- This way!

60
00:05:00,120 --> 00:05:03,240
Amelia!

61
00:05:39,840 --> 00:05:41,480
Amelia!

62
00:05:44,680 --> 00:05:47,000
Amelia?

63
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:51,480
Amelia?

64
00:05:53,480 --> 00:05:54,680
Amelia!

65
00:05:54,760 --> 00:05:58,120
TANNOY: Amelia Pond,
please go to the reception, please.

66
00:05:58,200 --> 00:06:00,200
Your aunt is waiting for you there.

67
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:01,880
Amelia Pond, please go to...

68
00:06:10,160 --> 00:06:11,760
Sorry.

69
00:07:31,200 --> 00:07:33,200
OK, kid.

70
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:35,280
This is where it gets complicated.

71
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:23,320
So the universe ended.

72
00:08:23,400 --> 00:08:25,280
You missed that.

73
00:08:25,360 --> 00:08:27,840
In 102 AD.

74
00:08:31,560 --> 00:08:34,160
I suppose this means you and I
never get born at all.

75
00:08:35,760 --> 00:08:38,520
Twice, in my case.

76
00:08:43,880 --> 00:08:45,880
You would have laughed at that.

77
00:08:47,960 --> 00:08:50,760
Please laugh!

78
00:08:55,040 --> 00:08:58,200
The Doctor said the universe
was huge and ridiculous,

79
00:08:58,280 --> 00:09:00,400
and sometimes there were miracles.

80
00:09:04,080 --> 00:09:08,400
I could do with
a ridiculous miracle about now.

81
00:09:08,960 --> 00:09:11,400
Rory! Listen, she's not dead.

82
00:09:11,480 --> 00:09:14,160
Well, she is dead,
but it's not the end of the world.

83
00:09:14,240 --> 00:09:15,760
Well, it is the end of the world.

84
00:09:15,840 --> 00:09:18,720
Actually, it's the end of the universe.
Oh, no. Hang on!

85
00:09:19,960 --> 00:09:22,480
Doctor? Doctor!

86
00:09:23,480 --> 00:09:26,760
- You need to get me out of the Pandorica.
- You're not in the Pandorica.

87
00:09:26,840 --> 00:09:29,200
Yes, I am. Well, I'm not now,
but I was back then.

88
00:09:29,320 --> 00:09:33,320
Well, back now from your point of view,
which is back then from my point of view.

89
00:09:33,400 --> 00:09:36,000
Time travel, you can't keep it straight
in your head.

90
00:09:36,080 --> 00:09:38,680
It's easy to open from the outside -
just point and press.

91
00:09:38,760 --> 00:09:40,440
Now go.

92
00:09:44,600 --> 00:09:49,200
Oh, when you're done, leave my screwdriver
in her top pocket. Good luck!

93
00:09:49,280 --> 00:09:52,080
What do you mean?

94
00:09:52,160 --> 00:09:53,640
Done what?

95
00:10:04,560 --> 00:10:06,160
How did you do that?

96
00:10:06,240 --> 00:10:07,960
You gave me this.

97
00:10:08,040 --> 00:10:10,520
No, I didn't.

98
00:10:10,600 --> 00:10:12,200
You did. Look at it.

99
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:24,560
Temporal energy. Same screwdriver, at
different points in its own time stream.

100
00:10:24,640 --> 00:10:27,680
Which means it was me who gave it
to you. Me from the future.

101
00:10:27,760 --> 00:10:30,120
I've got a future, that's nice.

102
00:10:30,200 --> 00:10:32,000
That's not.

103
00:10:32,080 --> 00:10:35,200
Yeah. What are they?

104
00:10:35,280 --> 00:10:41,600
History has collapsed. Whole races
have been deleted from existence.

105
00:10:41,680 --> 00:10:43,880
These are just like after-images.

106
00:10:45,800 --> 00:10:47,960
Echoes, fossils in time.

107
00:10:48,040 --> 00:10:51,720
- The footprints of the never-were.
- Er, what does that mean?

108
00:10:51,800 --> 00:10:54,680
Total event collapse. The universe
literally never happened.

109
00:10:54,760 --> 00:10:56,160
So, how can we be here?

110
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:57,400
What's keeping us safe?

111
00:10:57,480 --> 00:11:01,200
Nothing. Eye of the storm, that's all.
We're just the last light to go out.

112
00:11:01,280 --> 00:11:05,640
Amy. Where's Amy?

113
00:11:07,400 --> 00:11:09,120
I killed her.

114
00:11:10,680 --> 00:11:12,440
Oh, Rory!

115
00:11:13,440 --> 00:11:15,560
Doctor, what am I?

116
00:11:15,640 --> 00:11:20,560
You're a Nestene duplicate. A lump
of plastic with delusions of humanity.

117
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:23,240
But I'm Rory now.

118
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:25,640
Whatever was happening,
it's stopped.

119
00:11:25,720 --> 00:11:28,040
- I'm Rory!
- That's software talking.

120
00:11:28,120 --> 00:11:31,600
Can you help her?
Is there anything you can do?

121
00:11:31,680 --> 00:11:34,360
Yeah, probably, if I had the time.

122
00:11:34,440 --> 00:11:35,720
The time?!

123
00:11:35,800 --> 00:11:38,960
All of creation has just been
wiped from the sky.

124
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:42,040
Do you know how many lives
now never happened?

125
00:11:42,120 --> 00:11:44,360
All the people who never lived?

126
00:11:44,440 --> 00:11:47,880
Your girlfriend isn't more important
than the whole universe.

127
00:11:49,440 --> 00:11:51,440
She is to me!

128
00:11:53,280 --> 00:11:56,680
Welcome back, Rory Williams!

129
00:11:58,080 --> 00:11:59,160
Sorry, had to be sure.

130
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:03,080
Hell of a gun-arm you're packing there.
Right, we need to get her downstairs.

131
00:12:03,200 --> 00:12:07,360
And take that look off your plastic face.
You're getting married in the morning!

132
00:12:11,120 --> 00:12:15,600
- So you've got a plan, then?
- Bit of a plan, yeah.

133
00:12:15,720 --> 00:12:19,840
Memories are more powerful than you think,
and Amy Pond is not an ordinary girl.

134
00:12:19,920 --> 00:12:21,840
Grew up with a time crack in her wall,

135
00:12:21,920 --> 00:12:24,480
the universe pouring through
her dreams every night.

136
00:12:24,600 --> 00:12:28,600
The Nestenes took a memory print of her
and got more than they bargained for.

137
00:12:28,680 --> 00:12:32,560
Like you. Not just your face,
but your heart and your soul.

138
00:12:32,680 --> 00:12:37,360
I'm leaving her a message for when she
wakes up, so she knows what's happening.

139
00:12:42,560 --> 00:12:44,520
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. What are you doing?
- Saving her.

140
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:45,880
This box is the ultimate prison.

141
00:12:45,960 --> 00:12:48,600
You can't even escape by dying.
It forces you to stay alive.

142
00:12:48,680 --> 00:12:49,960
But she's already dead.

143
00:12:50,040 --> 00:12:52,800
Mostly dead. The Pandorica can
stasis-lock her that way.

144
00:12:52,880 --> 00:12:56,000
All it needs is a scan of her living DNA
and it'll restore her.

145
00:12:56,080 --> 00:12:59,720
- Where's it going to get that?
- In about 2,000 years.

146
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:06,280
Are you all right?

147
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:09,320
Who are you?

148
00:13:09,400 --> 00:13:13,440
I'm...fine.
I'm supposed to...rest.

149
00:13:13,520 --> 00:13:16,240
- Got to rest, the Doctor says.
- What doctor?

150
00:13:16,360 --> 00:13:20,760
He's in here. Left a message in my head
like I'm an answerphone. Where am I?

151
00:13:20,840 --> 00:13:22,760
Hang on.

152
00:13:22,840 --> 00:13:26,360
National Museum, right? I was here
once when I was a little...

153
00:13:27,720 --> 00:13:30,000
Yeah, complicated.

154
00:13:30,080 --> 00:13:32,280
Let's see, it's what...

155
00:13:34,440 --> 00:13:36,080
19967

156
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:39,480
Who are you?

157
00:13:39,560 --> 00:13:41,040
It's a long story.

158
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:44,640
Oh!

159
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:46,200
A very long story.

160
00:13:50,320 --> 00:13:53,000
She's going to be in that box
for 2,000 years?!

161
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:56,480
Yeah, but we're taking a shortcut.
River's Vortex Manipulator.

162
00:13:56,600 --> 00:14:00,560
Rubbish way to time travel, but
the universe is tiny now. We'll be fine.

163
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:03,120
So the future's still there, then?
Our world?

164
00:14:03,200 --> 00:14:05,480
A version of it.
Not quite the one you know.

165
00:14:05,560 --> 00:14:07,040
Earth alone in the sky.

166
00:14:07,120 --> 00:14:08,840
Let's go and have a look.

167
00:14:08,920 --> 00:14:10,560
You put your hand there.

168
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:13,440
Don't worry, should be safe.

169
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:15,600
That's not what I'm worried about.

170
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:20,840
She'll be fine.
Nothing can get into this box.

171
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:24,200
- You got in there.
- Well, there's only one of me. I counted.

172
00:14:24,280 --> 00:14:27,120
This box needs a guard.
I killed the last one.

173
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:30,720
No. Rory, no.
Don't even think about it.

174
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:31,760
She'll be all alone.

175
00:14:31,840 --> 00:14:33,520
- She won't feel it.
- You bet she won't!

176
00:14:33,640 --> 00:14:38,920
2,000 years, Rory. You won't even sleep,
you'd be conscious every second.

177
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:40,720
It would drive you mad.

178
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:43,720
Will she be safer if I stay?

179
00:14:43,800 --> 00:14:47,560
Look me in the eye
and tell me she wouldn't be safer.

180
00:14:47,640 --> 00:14:50,600
- Rory...
- Answer me!

181
00:14:52,600 --> 00:14:56,240
Yes. Obviously.

182
00:14:56,320 --> 00:14:58,800
Then how could I leave her?

183
00:15:00,360 --> 00:15:02,520
Why do you have to be so...

184
00:15:04,680 --> 00:15:06,440
...human?

185
00:15:06,520 --> 00:15:09,480
Because right now, I'm not.

186
00:15:14,440 --> 00:15:15,960
Listen to me.

187
00:15:16,080 --> 00:15:19,440
This is the last bit of advice
you're going to get in a very long time.

188
00:15:19,560 --> 00:15:23,640
You're living plastic, but not immortal.
I have no idea how long you'll last.

189
00:15:23,760 --> 00:15:27,400
And you're not indestructible.
Stay away from heat and radio signals.

190
00:15:27,480 --> 00:15:29,280
You can't heal or repair yourself.

191
00:15:29,360 --> 00:15:32,600
So, for God's sake, however bored
you get, stay out of...

192
00:15:49,320 --> 00:15:52,840
MAN: According to legend,
wherever the Pandorica was taken,

193
00:15:52,920 --> 00:15:54,720
throughout its long history,

194
00:15:54,800 --> 00:15:57,080
the Centurion would be there,
guarding it.

195
00:15:57,160 --> 00:16:01,160
He appears as an iconic image
in the artwork of many cultures,

196
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:04,480
and there are several documented
accounts of his appearances

197
00:16:04,560 --> 00:16:07,200
and his warnings to the many
who attempted to open the box

198
00:16:07,280 --> 00:16:09,920
- before its time.
- (AIR-RAID SIREN)

199
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:14,800
His last recorded appearance
was during the London Blitz in 1941.

200
00:16:14,880 --> 00:16:18,880
The warehouse where the Pandorica
was stored was destroyed

201
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:23,640
by incendiary bombs, but the box itself
was found the next morning,

202
00:16:23,720 --> 00:16:26,080
a safe distance from the blaze.

203
00:16:26,160 --> 00:16:29,080
There are eyewitness accounts
from the night of the fire

204
00:16:29,160 --> 00:16:32,160
of a figure in Roman dress,
carrying the box

205
00:16:32,240 --> 00:16:34,040
from the flames. Since then,

206
00:16:34,120 --> 00:16:37,400
there have been no sightings
of the Lone Centurion,

207
00:16:37,480 --> 00:16:41,800
and many have speculated
that if he ever existed,

208
00:16:41,880 --> 00:16:44,160
he perished in the fires of that night,

209
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:46,760
performing one last act of devotion

210
00:16:46,840 --> 00:16:51,040
to the box he had pledged to protect
for nearly 2,000 years.

211
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:52,720
Rory...

212
00:16:52,800 --> 00:16:55,640
Oh, Rory...

213
00:16:55,720 --> 00:16:58,680
- Exterminate!
- What's that?

214
00:16:58,760 --> 00:17:01,320
Exterminate!

215
00:17:01,400 --> 00:17:03,120
Trouble.

216
00:17:03,200 --> 00:17:05,760
Oh! Two of you? Complicated.

217
00:17:05,840 --> 00:17:08,080
Exterminate!

218
00:17:08,160 --> 00:17:09,800
Weapons systems restoring.

219
00:17:09,880 --> 00:17:12,760
- Come along, Ponds.
- Exterminate!

220
00:17:14,480 --> 00:17:16,320
What are we doing?

221
00:17:16,400 --> 00:17:18,920
Well, we are running into a dead end,
where I'll have a brilliant plan

222
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:20,600
that basically involves
not being in one.

223
00:17:20,680 --> 00:17:22,200
What's going on?

224
00:17:22,280 --> 00:17:24,560
Get out of here. Go! Just run!

225
00:17:24,640 --> 00:17:27,200
Drop the device!

226
00:17:27,280 --> 00:17:28,600
It's not a weapon. Scan it.
It's not a weapon,

227
00:17:28,680 --> 00:17:30,120
and you don't have the power to waste.

228
00:17:30,200 --> 00:17:34,600
Scans indicate intruder unarmed.

229
00:17:34,680 --> 00:17:36,000
Do you think(?)

230
00:17:39,920 --> 00:17:43,640
Vision impaired! Vision...

231
00:17:46,520 --> 00:17:49,040
Amy?

232
00:17:49,120 --> 00:17:50,800
Rory...

233
00:17:56,720 --> 00:17:59,760
I'm sorry. I'm sorry. I couldn't help it,
it just happened.

234
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:00,880
Oh, shut up.

235
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:04,720
Yeah, shut up, cos we've got to go.
Come on!

236
00:18:04,800 --> 00:18:08,320
I waited. 2,000 years, I waited for you.

237
00:18:08,400 --> 00:18:10,720
No, still shut up.

238
00:18:10,800 --> 00:18:12,160
And break.

239
00:18:12,240 --> 00:18:13,680
And breathe!

240
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:17,800
Well, somebody didn't get out much
for 2,000 years.

241
00:18:18,880 --> 00:18:21,440
I'm thirsty. Can I get a drink?

242
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:24,040
Oh, it's all mouths today, isn't it?!

243
00:18:27,160 --> 00:18:31,280
The light!
The light from the Pandorica,

244
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:33,520
it must have hit the Dalek.

245
00:18:33,600 --> 00:18:35,960
(ELECTRONIC WHIRRING)

246
00:18:36,040 --> 00:18:38,400
Out, out, out!

247
00:18:44,200 --> 00:18:47,200
So, 2,000 years. How did you do?

248
00:18:47,280 --> 00:18:49,040
- Kept out of trouble.
- Oh.

249
00:18:52,040 --> 00:18:53,080
How?

250
00:18:53,160 --> 00:18:54,120
Unsuccessfully.

251
00:18:54,200 --> 00:18:55,200
The mop!

252
00:18:55,240 --> 00:18:59,200
That's how you looked all those years ago
when you gave me the sonic.

253
00:18:59,280 --> 00:19:01,680
Ah! Well, no time to lose, then.

254
00:19:03,560 --> 00:19:06,480
Rory! Listen, she's not dead.

255
00:19:06,560 --> 00:19:09,360
Well, she /sdead,
but it's not the end of the world.

256
00:19:09,440 --> 00:19:11,480
Oops, sorry.

257
00:19:11,560 --> 00:19:13,440
How can he do that? Is he magic?

258
00:19:14,840 --> 00:19:17,120
You need to get me
out of the Pandorica.

259
00:19:17,200 --> 00:19:18,520
But you're not /77 the Pandorica.

260
00:19:18,600 --> 00:19:20,760
Yes, I am. Well, I'm not now.
But I was back then.

261
00:19:22,040 --> 00:19:23,520
Right...let's go, then.

262
00:19:24,920 --> 00:19:26,200
Wait!

263
00:19:26,280 --> 00:19:30,240
Now I don't have the sonic -
I just gave it to Rory 2,000 years ago.

264
00:19:30,360 --> 00:19:34,160
And when you're done,
leave my screwdriver in her top pocket.

265
00:19:35,840 --> 00:19:37,440
Right, then.

266
00:19:38,800 --> 00:19:40,160
Off we go!

267
00:19:40,240 --> 00:19:45,720
No, hang on.
How did you know...to come here?

268
00:19:48,880 --> 00:19:52,000
Ah, my handwriting. OK!

269
00:20:03,360 --> 00:20:05,520
There you go, drink up!

270
00:20:05,600 --> 00:20:08,240
What is that?
How are you doing that?

271
00:20:08,320 --> 00:20:11,320
Vortex Manipulator - cheap and nasty
time travel. Very bad for you.

272
00:20:11,400 --> 00:20:12,440
I'm trying to give it up.

273
00:20:12,520 --> 00:20:15,520
- Where are we going?
- The roof.

274
00:20:25,800 --> 00:20:30,680
Doctor, it's you. How can it be you?

275
00:20:30,760 --> 00:20:33,360
- AMY: Doctor, ls that you?
- Yeah, it's me.

276
00:20:34,920 --> 00:20:36,800
Me from the future.

277
00:20:39,680 --> 00:20:42,000
(FUTURE DOCTOR WHISPERS)

278
00:20:50,400 --> 00:20:52,360
Are you...?

279
00:20:52,440 --> 00:20:55,440
I mean, is he...

280
00:20:55,520 --> 00:20:58,080
is he dead?

281
00:20:58,160 --> 00:20:59,600
What?

282
00:21:01,120 --> 00:21:04,800
Dead? Yes, yes. Of course he's dead.

283
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:07,040
Right, I've got 12 minutes,
that's good.

284
00:21:07,120 --> 00:21:09,640
12 minutes to live? How is that good?!

285
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:12,720
You can do loads in 12 minutes - suck
a mint, buy a sledge, have a fast bath.

286
00:21:12,800 --> 00:21:14,760
- Come on, the roof!
- We can't leave you here, dead.

287
00:21:14,840 --> 00:21:16,840
Oh, good - are you in charge now(?)

288
00:21:16,960 --> 00:21:19,960
So, tell me,
what are we going to do about Amelia?

289
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:24,320
Where did she go?

290
00:21:26,280 --> 00:21:27,320
Amelia?

291
00:21:27,400 --> 00:21:28,960
There is no Amelia.

292
00:21:29,040 --> 00:21:32,040
From now on, there never was.
History is still collapsing.

293
00:21:32,120 --> 00:21:35,720
- How can I'be here if she's not?
- You're an anomaly. We all are.

294
00:21:35,800 --> 00:21:38,400
We're all hanging on at the eye
of the storm, but the eye is closing,

295
00:21:38,480 --> 00:21:41,200
and if we don't do something fast,
reality will never have happened.

296
00:21:41,280 --> 00:21:44,880
Today, just dying is a result.
Now, come on!

297
00:21:46,440 --> 00:21:47,880
He won't die.

298
00:21:47,960 --> 00:21:49,560
Time can be rewritten.

299
00:21:49,640 --> 00:21:52,640
He'll find a way. I know he will.

300
00:21:52,720 --> 00:21:54,200
DOCTOR: Move it! Come on!

301
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:06,520
- (ELECTRONIC WHIRRING)
- Restore...

302
00:22:08,320 --> 00:22:16,000
Restore...!

303
00:22:20,240 --> 00:22:22,680
AMY: What, it's morning already?
How did that happen?

304
00:22:22,760 --> 00:22:25,520
History is shrinking.
Is anybody listening to me?

305
00:22:25,600 --> 00:22:28,480
Universe is collapsing.
We don't have much time left.

306
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:29,520
What are you doing?

307
00:22:29,600 --> 00:22:32,160
- Looking for the TARDIS.
- But the TARDIS exploded.

308
00:22:32,240 --> 00:22:34,600
OK, then,
I'm looking for an exploding TARDIS.

309
00:22:34,720 --> 00:22:38,240
I don't understand. So, the TARDIS blew up
and took the universe with it.

310
00:22:38,320 --> 00:22:42,200
- But why would it do that? How?
- Good question for another day.

311
00:22:42,280 --> 00:22:44,680
The question for now is...total event
collapse means that every star

312
00:22:44,800 --> 00:22:48,080
in the universe never happened.
Not one single one of them ever shone.

313
00:22:48,160 --> 00:22:53,040
So, if all the stars that ever were
are gone, then what...is that?

314
00:22:54,720 --> 00:22:58,440
Like I said,
I'm looking for an exploding TARDIS.

315
00:22:59,560 --> 00:23:02,320
- But that's the sun.
-Is it?

316
00:23:02,400 --> 00:23:05,640
Here's the noise
that sun is making right now.

317
00:23:05,720 --> 00:23:09,640
- (METALLIC THRUMMING)
- That's my TARDIS burning up.

318
00:23:09,720 --> 00:23:13,000
That's what's been keeping
the Earth warm.

319
00:23:13,080 --> 00:23:16,160
Doctor, there's something else.

320
00:23:16,240 --> 00:23:17,440
There's a voice.

321
00:23:17,520 --> 00:23:19,000
(WHISPERING)

322
00:23:19,080 --> 00:23:22,840
- I can't hear anything.
- Trust the plastic.

323
00:23:24,440 --> 00:23:25,880
RIVER: I'm sorry, my love.

324
00:23:25,960 --> 00:23:29,200
Doctor, that's River.
How can she be up there?

325
00:23:29,280 --> 00:23:31,680
It must be like a recording
or something.

326
00:23:31,760 --> 00:23:34,440
No, it's not a recording.
Of course - the emergency protocols.

327
00:23:34,560 --> 00:23:37,960
The TARDIS has sealed off the control room
and put her into a time loop to save her.

328
00:23:38,040 --> 00:23:40,480
She is right at the heart
of the explosion.

329
00:23:40,560 --> 00:23:41,800
I'm sorry, my love.

330
00:23:41,880 --> 00:23:43,560
I'm sorry, my love.

331
00:23:54,760 --> 00:23:56,280
I'm sorry, my love.

332
00:24:06,680 --> 00:24:09,160
I'm sorry, my love.

333
00:24:15,400 --> 00:24:17,440
Hi, honey. I'm home.

334
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:21,280
And what sort of time
do you call this?

335
00:24:21,360 --> 00:24:22,920
Amy!

336
00:24:24,280 --> 00:24:27,080
- And the plastic Centurion?
- It's OK, he's on our side.

337
00:24:27,160 --> 00:24:28,160
- Really?
- Yeah.

338
00:24:28,200 --> 00:24:32,960
I dated a Nestene duplicate once -
swappable head, it did keep things fresh.

339
00:24:33,040 --> 00:24:35,520
Right, then, I have questions.

340
00:24:35,600 --> 00:24:37,480
But number one is this -

341
00:24:37,560 --> 00:24:41,280
what in the name of sanity
have you got on your head?

342
00:24:41,360 --> 00:24:45,280
It's a fez. I wear a fez now.
Fezzes are cool.

343
00:24:47,040 --> 00:24:48,240
Oh!

344
00:24:49,960 --> 00:24:52,640
Exterminate!

345
00:24:52,720 --> 00:24:55,920
Run, run! Move, move! Go! Come on!

346
00:25:05,640 --> 00:25:08,080
- Doctor, come on.
- Shh!

347
00:25:08,160 --> 00:25:10,720
It's moving away,
finding another way in.

348
00:25:10,800 --> 00:25:13,680
It needs to restore its power
before it can attack again.

349
00:25:13,760 --> 00:25:17,480
Now, that means we've got exactly...
four and a half minutes

350
00:25:17,560 --> 00:25:18,520
before it's at lethal capacity.

351
00:25:18,600 --> 00:25:21,360
- How do you know?
- Because that's when it's due to kill me.

352
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:24,880
- Kill you? What do you mean, kill you?
- Oh, shut up, never mind.

353
00:25:24,960 --> 00:25:26,560
How can that Dalek even exist?

354
00:25:26,640 --> 00:25:29,400
It was erased from time
and then it came back. How?

355
00:25:29,480 --> 00:25:31,560
You said the light
from the Pandorica...

356
00:25:31,640 --> 00:25:35,560
It's not a light, it's a restoration
field, but never mind. Call it a light.

357
00:25:35,640 --> 00:25:39,160
That light brought Amy back,
but how could it bring back a Dalek

358
00:25:39,240 --> 00:25:41,240
when the Daleks have never existed?

359
00:25:41,320 --> 00:25:43,520
OK, tell us.

360
00:25:43,600 --> 00:25:46,400
When the TARDIS blew up,
it caused a total event collapse,

361
00:25:46,480 --> 00:25:47,520
a time explosion.

362
00:25:47,560 --> 00:25:50,560
And that explosion blasted every atom
in every moment of the universe,

363
00:25:50,640 --> 00:25:52,160
except...

364
00:25:52,240 --> 00:25:55,160
Except inside the Pandorica.

365
00:25:55,240 --> 00:25:57,720
The perfect prison.
And inside it, perfectly preserved,

366
00:25:57,800 --> 00:25:59,640
a few billion atoms
of the universe as it was.

367
00:25:59,760 --> 00:26:03,680
In theory, you could extrapolate the whole
universe from a single one of them,

368
00:26:03,800 --> 00:26:07,880
like cloning a body from a single cell.
And we've got the bumper family pack.

369
00:26:07,960 --> 00:26:09,520
No, no, too fast, I'm not getting it.

370
00:26:09,640 --> 00:26:13,440
The box contains a memory of the universe,
and the light transmits the memory.

371
00:26:13,520 --> 00:26:16,440
- And that's how we're going to do it.
- Do what?

372
00:26:16,520 --> 00:26:20,720
Relight the fire.
Reboot the universe.

373
00:26:20,800 --> 00:26:22,320
Come on!

374
00:26:22,400 --> 00:26:25,560
RIVER: Doctor, you're being
completely ridiculous.

375
00:26:25,640 --> 00:26:28,840
The Pandorica partially restored
one Dalek.

376
00:26:28,920 --> 00:26:32,000
If it can't even reboot
a single life form properly,

377
00:26:32,080 --> 00:26:33,720
how will it reboot the whole of reality?

378
00:26:33,800 --> 00:26:35,840
What if we give it
a moment of infinite power?

379
00:26:35,920 --> 00:26:37,840
What if we can transmit the light
from the Pandorica

380
00:26:37,920 --> 00:26:39,920
to every particle of space and time
simultaneously?

381
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:41,720
Well, that would be lovely, dear,

382
00:26:41,800 --> 00:26:44,400
but we can't,
because it's completely impossible.

383
00:26:44,480 --> 00:26:49,440
Ah, no, you see, it's not.
It's almost completely impossible.

384
00:26:49,520 --> 00:26:52,120
- One spark is all we need.
- For what?

385
00:26:52,200 --> 00:26:54,360
Big Bang 2! Now, listen...

386
00:26:55,920 --> 00:26:59,880
- Exterminate! Exterminate!
- RORY: Get back! River, get back now!

387
00:26:59,960 --> 00:27:01,840
Exterminate!

388
00:27:05,560 --> 00:27:09,080
Doctor. Doctor, it's me, River.
Doctor, can you hear me?

389
00:27:09,160 --> 00:27:10,960
What is it? What do you need?

390
00:27:11,040 --> 00:27:13,800
- (BEEP)
- Where did he go?

391
00:27:13,880 --> 00:27:15,960
Damn it, he could be anywhere.

392
00:27:16,040 --> 00:27:19,000
He went downstairs...12 minutes ago.

393
00:27:19,080 --> 00:27:21,320
- Show me!
- River...

394
00:27:21,400 --> 00:27:23,840
he died.

395
00:27:23,920 --> 00:27:28,360
Systems restoring!
You will be exterminated!

396
00:27:28,440 --> 00:27:30,800
We've got to move.
That thing's coming back to life.

397
00:27:30,880 --> 00:27:34,200
You go to the Doctor.
I'L be right with you.

398
00:27:39,560 --> 00:27:42,440
You will be exterminated!

399
00:27:42,520 --> 00:27:45,960
Not yet -
your systems are still restoring,

400
00:27:46,040 --> 00:27:49,160
which means your shield density
is compromised.

401
00:27:49,240 --> 00:27:54,080
One Alpha-Mezon burst through your
eye stalk would kill you stone dead.

402
00:27:54,160 --> 00:27:58,400
Records indicate you will show mercy.

403
00:27:58,480 --> 00:28:00,320
You are an associate of the Doctor's.

404
00:28:00,400 --> 00:28:04,480
I'm River Song.
Check your records again.

405
00:28:06,280 --> 00:28:07,240
Mercy!

406
00:28:07,320 --> 00:28:09,760
- Say it again.
- Mercy!

407
00:28:09,840 --> 00:28:12,160
One more time.

408
00:28:12,240 --> 00:28:15,360
Mercy!

409
00:28:17,600 --> 00:28:21,880
How could he have moved?
He was dead!

410
00:28:21,960 --> 00:28:25,560
Doctor? Doctor!

411
00:28:25,640 --> 00:28:27,480
But he was dead!

412
00:28:27,560 --> 00:28:29,000
Who told you that?

413
00:28:29,080 --> 00:28:32,480
- He did.
- Rule one...the Doctor lies.

414
00:28:32,560 --> 00:28:35,480
- Where's the Dalek?
- It died.

415
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:39,680
Doctor!

416
00:28:43,960 --> 00:28:46,480
Why did he tell us he was dead?

417
00:28:46,560 --> 00:28:49,120
We were a diversion.

418
00:28:49,200 --> 00:28:53,920
Long as the Dalek was chasing us,
he could work down here.

419
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:55,680
Doctor, can you hear me?

420
00:28:55,760 --> 00:28:57,240
What were you doing?

421
00:29:02,440 --> 00:29:03,960
What's happening?

422
00:29:04,040 --> 00:29:09,000
Reality's collapsing.
It's speeding up. Look at this room.

423
00:29:09,080 --> 00:29:13,360
- AMY: Where did everything go?
- RIVER: History's being erased.

424
00:29:13,440 --> 00:29:17,480
Time's running out.
Doctor, what were you doing? Tell us!

425
00:29:17,560 --> 00:29:19,520
Doctor?

426
00:29:23,760 --> 00:29:25,240
Big...

427
00:29:25,320 --> 00:29:26,720
Bang...

428
00:29:26,800 --> 00:29:27,800
2.

429
00:29:27,880 --> 00:29:30,120
The Big Bang.

430
00:29:30,200 --> 00:29:32,560
That's the beginning
of the universe, right?

431
00:29:32,640 --> 00:29:35,560
What, and Big Bang 2
is the bang that brings us back?

432
00:29:35,640 --> 00:29:36,720
Is that what you mean?

433
00:29:38,480 --> 00:29:39,480
Oh...

434
00:29:39,560 --> 00:29:43,200
- What?
- The TARDIS is still burning.

435
00:29:43,280 --> 00:29:45,440
It's exploding at every point
in history.

436
00:29:45,520 --> 00:29:48,680
If you threw the Pandorica
into the explosion,

437
00:29:48,760 --> 00:29:51,480
- right into the heart of the fire...
- Then what?

438
00:29:51,560 --> 00:29:53,880
Then let there be light.

439
00:29:53,960 --> 00:29:59,040
The light from the Pandorica
would explode everywhere at once,

440
00:29:59,120 --> 00:30:00,280
just like he said.

441
00:30:00,360 --> 00:30:03,880
And that would work?
That would bring everything back?

442
00:30:03,960 --> 00:30:08,480
A restoration field,
powered by an exploding TARDIS,

443
00:30:08,560 --> 00:30:10,600
happening at every moment in history.

444
00:30:10,680 --> 00:30:14,560
Oh, that's brilliant.
It might even work!

445
00:30:16,320 --> 00:30:19,760
He's wired the Vortex Manipulator
to the rest of the box.

446
00:30:19,840 --> 00:30:22,880
- Why?
- So he can take it with him.

447
00:30:22,960 --> 00:30:28,200
He's going to fly the Pandorica
into the heart of the explosion.

448
00:30:41,320 --> 00:30:44,000
- Are you OK?
- Are you?

449
00:30:44,080 --> 00:30:45,520
No.

450
00:30:45,600 --> 00:30:46,880
Well, shut up, then!

451
00:30:53,480 --> 00:30:56,000
Amy...he wants to talk to you.

452
00:30:56,080 --> 00:30:59,040
So, what happens here? Big Bang 2?

453
00:30:59,120 --> 00:31:00,960
What happens to us?

454
00:31:01,040 --> 00:31:03,120
We all wake up where we ought to be.

455
00:31:03,200 --> 00:31:06,040
None of this ever happens,
and we don't remember it.

456
00:31:07,080 --> 00:31:08,720
River...

457
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:11,760
tell me he comes back too.

458
00:31:11,840 --> 00:31:14,720
The Doctor will be
at the heart of the explosion.

459
00:31:14,800 --> 00:31:16,160
So?

460
00:31:16,240 --> 00:31:19,200
So all the cracks in time will close,

461
00:31:19,280 --> 00:31:21,320
but he'll be on the wrong side -

462
00:31:21,400 --> 00:31:24,440
trapped in the never-space,
the void between the worlds.

463
00:31:25,480 --> 00:31:28,880
All memory of him will be purged
from the universe.

464
00:31:28,960 --> 00:31:31,600
He will never have been born.

465
00:31:31,680 --> 00:31:34,480
Now, please...

466
00:31:34,560 --> 00:31:37,160
he wants to talk to you before he goes.

467
00:31:37,240 --> 00:31:38,800
Not to you?

468
00:31:38,880 --> 00:31:41,520
He doesn't really know me yet.

469
00:31:43,480 --> 00:31:44,840
Now he never will.

470
00:32:07,560 --> 00:32:09,320
Hi.

471
00:32:13,800 --> 00:32:15,240
Amy Pond.

472
00:32:16,920 --> 00:32:19,120
The girl who waited.

473
00:32:19,200 --> 00:32:21,120
All night in your garden.

474
00:32:22,680 --> 00:32:25,840
- Was it worth it?
- Shut up. Of course it was.

475
00:32:27,400 --> 00:32:31,440
You asked me why I was taking you
with me, and I said...

476
00:32:31,520 --> 00:32:32,840
"No reason."

477
00:32:35,280 --> 00:32:37,680
- I was lying.
- It's not important.

478
00:32:37,760 --> 00:32:40,800
Yeah, it's the most important thing
left in the universe.

479
00:32:42,360 --> 00:32:44,120
It's why I'm doing this.

480
00:32:45,960 --> 00:32:48,080
Amy, your house was too big.

481
00:32:48,160 --> 00:32:51,960
That big, empty house.

482
00:32:52,040 --> 00:32:54,280
- Just you.
- And Aunt Sharon.

483
00:32:54,360 --> 00:32:57,440
Where were your mum and dad?
Where was...

484
00:32:57,520 --> 00:32:59,960
everybody who lived
in that big house?

485
00:33:01,960 --> 00:33:04,800
- I lost my mum and dad.
- How?

486
00:33:04,880 --> 00:33:06,960
What happened to them?

487
00:33:07,040 --> 00:33:09,520
Where did they go?

488
00:33:09,600 --> 00:33:11,760
I...

489
00:33:11,840 --> 00:33:13,840
-I don't...
- It's OK, it's OK.

490
00:33:13,920 --> 00:33:16,400
Don't panic. It's not your fault.

491
00:33:17,480 --> 00:33:20,000
I don't even remember.

492
00:33:20,080 --> 00:33:22,200
There was a crack in time
in the wall of your bedroom.

493
00:33:22,280 --> 00:33:26,920
And it's been eating away
at your life for a long time now.

494
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:29,680
Amy Pond...

495
00:33:29,760 --> 00:33:31,840
all alone.

496
00:33:31,920 --> 00:33:34,160
The girl who didn't make sense.

497
00:33:35,880 --> 00:33:38,000
How could I resist?

498
00:33:38,080 --> 00:33:40,920
But how could I just forget?

499
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:43,880
Nothing is ever forgotten,

500
00:33:43,960 --> 00:33:45,840
not really.

501
00:33:45,920 --> 00:33:47,840
But you have to try.

502
00:33:50,640 --> 00:33:52,880
RIVER: Doctor! It's speeding up!

503
00:33:56,080 --> 00:33:58,960
There's going to be a very big bang -
Big Bang 2.

504
00:33:59,040 --> 00:34:01,600
Try and remember your family,
and they'll be there.

505
00:34:01,680 --> 00:34:03,720
How can I remember them
if they never existed?

506
00:34:03,800 --> 00:34:06,040
Because...you're special.

507
00:34:06,120 --> 00:34:09,440
That crack in your wall,
all that time,

508
00:34:09,520 --> 00:34:13,400
the universe pouring into your head.

509
00:34:13,480 --> 00:34:16,760
You brought Rory back -
you can bring them back too.

510
00:34:16,840 --> 00:34:19,080
You just remember...

511
00:34:19,160 --> 00:34:21,600
and they'll be there.

512
00:34:21,680 --> 00:34:24,600
- You won't.
- You'll have your family back.

513
00:34:25,480 --> 00:34:28,360
You won't need your imaginary friend
any more.

514
00:34:29,640 --> 00:34:31,280
Ha!

515
00:34:31,360 --> 00:34:32,960
Amy Pond...

516
00:34:33,040 --> 00:34:35,480
crying over me, eh?

517
00:34:35,560 --> 00:34:38,640
- Guess what?
- What?

518
00:34:38,720 --> 00:34:41,000
Gotcha!

519
00:34:46,600 --> 00:34:48,760
(CRASHING)

520
00:34:48,840 --> 00:34:50,560
Back! Get back!

521
00:34:57,840 --> 00:34:59,640
(BEEPING)

522
00:34:59,720 --> 00:35:02,640
(PANTS)

523
00:35:03,520 --> 00:35:05,080
(B EEPING)

524
00:35:05,160 --> 00:35:06,640
It's from the Doctor.

525
00:35:06,720 --> 00:35:08,200
What does it say?

526
00:35:09,680 --> 00:35:11,480
"Geronimo."

527
00:35:21,520 --> 00:35:24,280
(GROANS AND PANTS)

528
00:36:00,800 --> 00:36:02,320
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

529
00:36:02,400 --> 00:36:03,400
Oh!

530
00:36:03,480 --> 00:36:05,000
OK.

531
00:36:05,080 --> 00:36:08,640
I escaped, then. Brilliant!

532
00:36:08,720 --> 00:36:10,160
I love it when I do that.

533
00:36:10,240 --> 00:36:12,400
Legs, yes.

534
00:36:12,480 --> 00:36:14,440
Bow tie, cool.

535
00:36:15,640 --> 00:36:17,320
I can buy a fez.

536
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:19,240
DOCTOR: Now, the beach...
the beach is the best.

537
00:36:19,320 --> 00:36:20,600
Automatic sand.

538
00:36:20,680 --> 00:36:23,520
AMY: Automatic sand?
What does that mean?

539
00:36:23,600 --> 00:36:26,120
- DOCTOR: It's automated, totally.
- Oh.

540
00:36:26,200 --> 00:36:27,200
Cleans up the lolly sticks...

541
00:36:27,280 --> 00:36:31,160
No, hang on! That's last week
when we went to Space Florida.

542
00:36:31,240 --> 00:36:32,440
I'm rewinding.

543
00:36:32,520 --> 00:36:36,200
My-my-my time stream...unravelling,

544
00:36:36,280 --> 00:36:37,520
erasing.

545
00:36:39,600 --> 00:36:41,440
Closing.

546
00:36:44,640 --> 00:36:46,560
Hello, universe.

547
00:36:46,640 --> 00:36:48,640
Goodbye, Doctor.

548
00:36:52,720 --> 00:36:54,320
Amy?

549
00:37:02,560 --> 00:37:03,960
Amy?

550
00:37:10,720 --> 00:37:11,680
(MIAOWING)

551
00:37:11,760 --> 00:37:12,760
Ah!

552
00:37:12,840 --> 00:37:15,920
Three weeks ago, when she put
the card in the window. Amy!

553
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:18,080
I need to tell you something!

554
00:37:19,640 --> 00:37:21,080
She can hear me!

555
00:37:21,160 --> 00:37:23,040
But if she can hear me...

556
00:37:23,120 --> 00:37:24,920
(EERIE WIND BLOWS)

557
00:37:29,960 --> 00:37:33,680
DOCTOR: Good luck, everyone. Behave.
Do not let that girl open her eyes.

558
00:37:33,760 --> 00:37:36,840
Amy, later!
River, going to need your computer.

559
00:37:44,440 --> 00:37:47,400
Amy, you need to start trusting me.

560
00:37:47,520 --> 00:37:51,240
- It's never been more important.
- But you don't always tell me the truth.

561
00:37:51,320 --> 00:37:55,080
If I always told you the truth,
I wouldn't need you to trust me.

562
00:37:55,160 --> 00:37:58,400
Doctor, the crack in my wall...

563
00:37:58,480 --> 00:38:00,240
how can it be here?

564
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:02,120
I don't know yet,
but I'm working it out.

565
00:38:02,200 --> 00:38:04,080
(WHIRRING)

566
00:38:08,520 --> 00:38:09,760
Now, listen.

567
00:38:09,840 --> 00:38:12,040
Remember what I told you
when you were seven?

568
00:38:12,120 --> 00:38:13,080
What did you tell me?

569
00:38:13,160 --> 00:38:15,080
No.

570
00:38:15,160 --> 00:38:16,480
No.

571
00:38:16,560 --> 00:38:18,120
That's not the point.

572
00:38:20,280 --> 00:38:22,200
You have to remember.

573
00:38:28,840 --> 00:38:32,000
Remember what? Doctor?

574
00:38:32,080 --> 00:38:33,520
(CRASHING)

575
00:38:33,600 --> 00:38:35,480
Doctor?

576
00:38:40,560 --> 00:38:42,880
Amelia's house.

577
00:38:42,960 --> 00:38:45,080
When she was seven.

578
00:38:46,280 --> 00:38:48,800
The night she waited.

579
00:38:52,640 --> 00:38:55,640
(OWL HOOTS)

580
00:39:03,720 --> 00:39:05,200
The girl who waited.

581
00:39:07,120 --> 00:39:08,800
Come here, you.

582
00:39:27,400 --> 00:39:28,880
It's funny.

583
00:39:31,320 --> 00:39:34,400
I thought, if you could hear me,
I could hang on somehow.

584
00:39:35,960 --> 00:39:37,440
Silly me.

585
00:39:38,840 --> 00:39:41,280
Silly old Doctor.

586
00:39:46,720 --> 00:39:49,040
When you wake up,

587
00:39:49,120 --> 00:39:51,960
you'll have a mum and dad...

588
00:39:52,040 --> 00:39:54,840
and you won't even remember me.

589
00:39:54,920 --> 00:39:58,960
Well, you'll remember me a little.

590
00:39:59,040 --> 00:40:01,800
I'L be a story in your head.

591
00:40:03,240 --> 00:40:05,600
But that's OK.

592
00:40:05,680 --> 00:40:07,840
We're all stories in the end.

593
00:40:09,400 --> 00:40:11,360
Just make it a good one, eh?

594
00:40:11,440 --> 00:40:13,480
Cos it was, you know.

595
00:40:13,560 --> 00:40:15,640
It was the best.

596
00:40:18,240 --> 00:40:20,400
A daft old man

597
00:40:20,480 --> 00:40:22,520
who stole a magic box

598
00:40:22,600 --> 00:40:24,680
and ran away.

599
00:40:27,640 --> 00:40:29,600
Did I ever tell you that I stole it?

600
00:40:29,680 --> 00:40:32,480
Well, I borrowed it.
I was always going to take it back.

601
00:40:35,120 --> 00:40:38,360
Oh, that box, Amy.

602
00:40:39,680 --> 00:40:42,680
You'll dream about that box.

603
00:40:42,760 --> 00:40:46,080
It'll never leave you.

604
00:40:46,160 --> 00:40:51,200
Big and little at the same time.

605
00:40:51,280 --> 00:40:53,040
Brand-new and ancient.

606
00:40:53,120 --> 00:40:57,880
And the bluest blue ever.

607
00:40:59,640 --> 00:41:02,400
And the times we had, eh?

608
00:41:02,480 --> 00:41:05,240
Would've had.

609
00:41:05,320 --> 00:41:06,800
Never had.

610
00:41:08,720 --> 00:41:11,400
In your dreams,
they'll still be there.

611
00:41:14,360 --> 00:41:17,760
The Doctor and Amy Pond.

612
00:41:21,200 --> 00:41:23,040
And the days that never came.

613
00:41:25,680 --> 00:41:28,160
(CRASHING AND METALLIC BUZZING)

614
00:41:30,360 --> 00:41:32,400
The cracks are closing.

615
00:41:36,320 --> 00:41:39,440
But they can't close properly
till I'm on the other side.

616
00:41:43,480 --> 00:41:45,480
I don't belong here any more.

617
00:41:51,560 --> 00:41:54,080
I think I'll skip
the rest of the rewind.

618
00:41:56,480 --> 00:41:59,080
I hate repeats.

619
00:42:02,280 --> 00:42:04,800
Live well. Love Rory.

620
00:42:07,560 --> 00:42:10,000
Bye-bye, Pond.

621
00:42:13,760 --> 00:42:16,440
(METALLIC WHOOSHING)

622
00:43:24,880 --> 00:43:27,320
- Morning!
- (AMY GASPS)

623
00:43:28,920 --> 00:43:30,560
You're my mum.

624
00:43:30,640 --> 00:43:33,240
- Oh, my God. You're my mum.
- Well, of course I'm your mum.

625
00:43:33,320 --> 00:43:36,080
What's the matter with you?
And this is your breakfast,

626
00:43:36,160 --> 00:43:37,320
which your father made,

627
00:43:37,400 --> 00:43:40,320
so feel free to tip it
out of the window if it's an atrocity.

628
00:43:40,400 --> 00:43:43,600
Downstairs, 10 minutes? Big day!

629
00:43:45,440 --> 00:43:48,200
Of course she's my mum.
Why is that surprising?

630
00:43:53,800 --> 00:43:55,640
Ah, Amelia.

631
00:43:55,720 --> 00:43:58,920
I fear I may have been using
the same joke book as the best man.

632
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:00,960
You're my tiny little dad!

633
00:44:01,040 --> 00:44:04,160
Amelia, why are you behaving
as if you've never seen us before?

634
00:44:04,240 --> 00:44:06,680
I don't know. It's just...

635
00:44:09,800 --> 00:44:11,280
Hello!

636
00:44:11,320 --> 00:44:13,440
AMY: Do you feel like you've forgotten
something really important?

637
00:44:13,560 --> 00:44:16,120
Do you feel like there's a great big thing
in your head

638
00:44:16,240 --> 00:44:18,840
and you feel like you should remember it
but you can't?

639
00:44:20,640 --> 00:44:21,760
Yep.

640
00:44:21,840 --> 00:44:23,960
Are you just saying yes
cos you're scared of me?

641
00:44:24,040 --> 00:44:25,640
RORY: Yep.

642
00:44:25,720 --> 00:44:27,240
- I love you.
- Yep.

643
00:44:27,320 --> 00:44:29,160
I mean, I love you too!

644
00:44:45,480 --> 00:44:48,000
(LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE)

645
00:44:51,760 --> 00:44:56,600
Ladies and gentlemen,
the father of the bride, Augustus Pond!

646
00:44:56,680 --> 00:44:58,080
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

647
00:45:01,960 --> 00:45:03,320
Sorry, everyone.

648
00:45:03,400 --> 00:45:08,920
I'L be another two minutes.
I'm just reviewing certain aspects.

649
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:12,800
Your father, Amelia,
will be the absolute death of me.

650
00:45:12,880 --> 00:45:15,120
Unless, of course,
I strike pre-emptively.

651
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:30,640
Amy?

652
00:45:30,720 --> 00:45:33,760
- You OK?
- Yeah, I'm fine. I'm...

653
00:45:33,840 --> 00:45:35,520
fine.

654
00:45:35,600 --> 00:45:38,720
Right. Er...

655
00:45:38,800 --> 00:45:40,640
You're crying.

656
00:45:40,720 --> 00:45:43,640
So I am. Why am I doing that?

657
00:45:43,720 --> 00:45:47,960
Because you're happy, probably.

658
00:45:48,040 --> 00:45:51,800
- Happy Mrs Rory. Happy, happy, happy.
- No.

659
00:45:51,880 --> 00:45:53,760
I'm sad.

660
00:45:53,840 --> 00:45:57,960
- I'm really, really sad.
- Great.

661
00:45:58,040 --> 00:46:00,080
Why am I sad?

662
00:46:00,160 --> 00:46:01,760
What's that?

663
00:46:03,320 --> 00:46:05,320
Oh, er, someone left it for you.

664
00:46:06,360 --> 00:46:08,480
- A woman.
- What is it?

665
00:46:08,560 --> 00:46:10,080
- It's a book.
- It's blank.

666
00:46:10,160 --> 00:46:11,840
It's a present.

667
00:46:11,920 --> 00:46:16,320
- But why?
- Well, you know the old saying...

668
00:46:16,400 --> 00:46:20,280
The old...wedding...thing.

669
00:46:21,400 --> 00:46:22,960
Huh?

670
00:46:28,560 --> 00:46:30,000
Amy?

671
00:46:30,080 --> 00:46:32,400
Hey...

672
00:46:34,240 --> 00:46:35,560
Ready now.

673
00:46:36,680 --> 00:46:39,040
Sorry about that.

674
00:46:39,120 --> 00:46:41,680
Last-minute adjustments
to certain aspects.

675
00:46:41,760 --> 00:46:43,200
Now, then,

676
00:46:43,280 --> 00:46:46,640
- it hardly seems a year...
- ( HIS VOICE FADES)

677
00:46:56,000 --> 00:46:58,760
(WIND BLOWS)

678
00:47:02,360 --> 00:47:05,760
DAD: ..at the age of six and announced
that the new head teacher wasn't real,

679
00:47:05,840 --> 00:47:07,720
because she looked like a cartoon...

680
00:47:07,800 --> 00:47:09,200
- Shut up, Dad!
- Amy?

681
00:47:09,280 --> 00:47:10,600
- Amelia?
- Sorry, but shut up, please!

682
00:47:10,680 --> 00:47:14,040
There's someone missing...
someone important.

683
00:47:14,120 --> 00:47:16,720
Someone so, so important.

684
00:47:16,800 --> 00:47:18,400
- Amy, what's wrong?
- Sorry.

685
00:47:18,480 --> 00:47:20,840
- (CLEARS HER THROAT)
- Sorry, everyone.

686
00:47:22,400 --> 00:47:23,880
But when I was a kid,

687
00:47:23,960 --> 00:47:27,400
- I had an imaginary friend.
- Oh, no, not this again.

688
00:47:27,480 --> 00:47:31,320
The raggedy Doctor.
My raggedy Doctor.

689
00:47:31,400 --> 00:47:33,080
But he wasn't imaginary.

690
00:47:34,880 --> 00:47:35,880
He was real.

691
00:47:37,640 --> 00:47:40,720
- The psychiatrists we sent her to!
- I remember you!

692
00:47:40,800 --> 00:47:42,480
I remember!

693
00:47:42,560 --> 00:47:45,640
I brought the others back -
I can bring you home too!

694
00:47:45,720 --> 00:47:47,800
Raggedy man, I remember you,

695
00:47:47,880 --> 00:47:50,920
and you are late for my wedding!

696
00:47:52,560 --> 00:47:54,840
(GLASSES CHINK)

697
00:47:57,960 --> 00:48:01,040
I found you. I found you in words,
like you knew I would.

698
00:48:01,120 --> 00:48:05,480
That's why you told me the story -
the brand-new, ancient blue box.

699
00:48:05,560 --> 00:48:08,240
Oh, clever. Very clever.

700
00:48:09,800 --> 00:48:11,680
Amy, what is it?

701
00:48:11,760 --> 00:48:13,400
Something old.

702
00:48:13,480 --> 00:48:15,200
Something new.

703
00:48:15,280 --> 00:48:16,360
Something borrowed.

704
00:48:16,440 --> 00:48:19,000
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

705
00:48:19,080 --> 00:48:20,480
Something blue.

706
00:48:27,280 --> 00:48:29,000
It's the Doctor!

707
00:48:31,920 --> 00:48:34,320
How did we forget the Doctor?

708
00:48:34,400 --> 00:48:38,920
I was plastic. He was the stripper
at my stag. Long story.

709
00:48:40,320 --> 00:48:43,920
OK, Doctor.
Did I surprise you this time?

710
00:48:46,640 --> 00:48:47,600
Er, yeah.

711
00:48:47,680 --> 00:48:50,040
Completely astonished.

712
00:48:50,120 --> 00:48:51,480
Never expected that.

713
00:48:52,520 --> 00:48:56,520
How lucky I happened
to be wearing this old thing.

714
00:48:56,600 --> 00:48:58,160
Hello, everyone!

715
00:48:58,240 --> 00:49:01,040
- I'm Amy's imaginary friend.
- (GUESTS EXCLAIM)

716
00:49:01,120 --> 00:49:02,800
But I came anyway.

717
00:49:04,160 --> 00:49:07,520
You absolutely, definitely
may kiss the bride.

718
00:49:07,600 --> 00:49:10,000
Amelia! From now on,
I shall be leaving the...

719
00:49:10,080 --> 00:49:14,800
kissing duties
to the brand-new Mr Pond.

720
00:49:14,880 --> 00:49:17,080
No, I'm not Mr Pond.

721
00:49:17,160 --> 00:49:19,800
- That's not how it works.
- Yeah, it is.

722
00:49:19,880 --> 00:49:22,160
- Yeah, it is.
- Right, then, everyone,

723
00:49:22,240 --> 00:49:23,920
I'LL move my box.

724
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:25,600
You're going to need the space.

725
00:49:26,760 --> 00:49:29,120
I only came for the dancing.

726
00:49:30,640 --> 00:49:33,800
(# QUEEN:
Crazy Little Thing Called Love)

727
00:49:33,880 --> 00:49:35,640
(GIGGLES)

728
00:49:35,720 --> 00:49:38,040
You're terrible!
That is embarrassing!

729
00:49:40,920 --> 00:49:43,480
That's it. That's good.
Keep it loose.

730
00:49:51,160 --> 00:49:55,400
(# JAMES MORRISON: You Give Me Something)

731
00:49:58,400 --> 00:49:59,800
2,000 years.

732
00:50:01,120 --> 00:50:02,800
The boy who waited.

733
00:50:04,560 --> 00:50:06,200
Good on you, mate.

734
00:50:08,360 --> 00:50:13,560
# You want to stay with me in the morning

735
00:50:14,600 --> 00:50:17,400
# You only hold me when I sleep... #

736
00:50:23,040 --> 00:50:24,640
RIVER: Did you dance?

737
00:50:24,720 --> 00:50:29,440
Well, you always dance at weddings,
don't you?

738
00:50:29,520 --> 00:50:30,760
You tell me.

739
00:50:30,840 --> 00:50:32,840
Spoilers!

740
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:36,760
The writing's all back,
but I didn't peek.

741
00:50:38,320 --> 00:50:39,800
Thank you.

742
00:50:46,480 --> 00:50:49,560
Are you married, River?

743
00:50:49,640 --> 00:50:51,120
Are you asking?

744
00:50:52,680 --> 00:50:54,440
Yes.

745
00:50:54,520 --> 00:50:56,280
Yes.

746
00:50:56,360 --> 00:50:57,720
No, hang on.

747
00:50:57,800 --> 00:50:59,880
Did you think
I was asking you to marry me,

748
00:50:59,960 --> 00:51:02,560
or-or-or asking if you were married?

749
00:51:02,640 --> 00:51:04,400
Yes.

750
00:51:04,480 --> 00:51:06,640
No, but was that "yes", or "yes"?

751
00:51:06,720 --> 00:51:09,120
Yes.

752
00:51:10,160 --> 00:51:11,840
River...

753
00:51:13,240 --> 00:51:14,800
...who are you?

754
00:51:15,800 --> 00:51:18,080
You're going
to find out very soon now.

755
00:51:19,280 --> 00:51:21,320
And I'm sorry,

756
00:51:21,400 --> 00:51:23,560
but that's when everything changes.

757
00:51:23,640 --> 00:51:25,320
(BEEP)

758
00:51:29,160 --> 00:51:31,080
Ah...

759
00:51:41,320 --> 00:51:42,360
Oi!

760
00:51:43,160 --> 00:51:46,200
Where are you off to? We haven't even had
a snog in the shrubbery yet.

761
00:51:46,280 --> 00:51:47,240
Amy!

762
00:51:47,320 --> 00:51:50,360
- Shut up, it's my wedding.
- Ourwedding.

763
00:51:50,440 --> 00:51:52,760
Sorry, you two -
shouldn't have slipped away.

764
00:51:52,840 --> 00:51:54,040
Bit busy, you know?

765
00:51:54,120 --> 00:51:58,400
You just saved the whole of space
and time. Take the evening off!

766
00:51:58,480 --> 00:51:59,760
Maybe a bit of tomorrow.

767
00:51:59,840 --> 00:52:02,840
Space and time isn't safe yet.
The TARDIS exploded for a reason.

768
00:52:02,920 --> 00:52:05,920
Something drew the TARDIS
to this particular date and blew it up.

769
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:08,200
- Why? And why now?
- (PHONE RINGS)

770
00:52:08,280 --> 00:52:11,320
The silence, whatever it is,
is still out there, and I have to...

771
00:52:11,400 --> 00:52:12,600
Excuse me a moment. Hello!

772
00:52:12,680 --> 00:52:15,400
Oh, hello.

773
00:52:15,480 --> 00:52:17,680
I'm sorry, this is a very bad line.

774
00:52:17,760 --> 00:52:21,320
No, but that's not possible.
She was sealed into the Seventh Obelisk.

775
00:52:21,400 --> 00:52:22,960
I was at the prayer meeting.

776
00:52:23,040 --> 00:52:24,960
Well, no, I get that it's important.

777
00:52:25,040 --> 00:52:29,240
An Egyptian goddess loose
on the Orient Express.

778
00:52:29,320 --> 00:52:31,080
In space.

779
00:52:31,160 --> 00:52:32,200
Give us a mo.

780
00:52:32,280 --> 00:52:35,800
Sorry, something's come up.
This will have to be goodbye.

781
00:52:35,880 --> 00:52:38,840
Yeah, I think it's goodbye.
Do you think it's goodbye?

782
00:52:38,920 --> 00:52:40,560
Definitely goodbye.

783
00:52:43,960 --> 00:52:45,800
Goodbye!

784
00:52:47,080 --> 00:52:49,080
Goodbye.

785
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:54,160
Don't worry about a thing,
Your Majesty.

786
00:52:54,240 --> 00:52:56,600
We're on our way.

787
00:53:02,520 --> 00:53:05,080
(METALLIC THRUMMING)

